data.name: label1.Text
data.value: This list view shows what is possible using only the IDE. Each column has been told which aspect to display, plus: Birthday and Hourly Rate columns have format strings; Person and Occupation columns have minimum and maximum widths; Year of birth column is fixed width; Comments is a space filler. The Comments header shows a tool tip. All of this configuration, even the overlay image, was done within the IDE.

data.name: label2.Text
data.value: This list view shows what is possible. It shows: owner drawn rendering (check out owner drawing in Tile view!); alternate line colouring; super-doopers grouping (trying grouping on 'Cooking Skill' column); adding extra information to the 'Tile' view; dynamic tool tips for cells (hold down Control key to see); full drag and drop handling (drop someone on some else to "marry" them).

data.name: label3.Text
data.value: The DataListView (below) is sourced from the data table above. Changes to the data table are automatically reflected in the listview. This pane also shows FormatCell events: Put 'red', 'green', 'blue', 'italic' or 'bold' in a data field to see the formatter at work. It also shows animated GIFs in action (though why you would ever want those, I don't know). The 'Name' column wraps text rather than truncating it (owner drawn only).

data.name: label4.Text
data.value: Listviews aren't really the best interface for lists of hundreds of thousands of item -- but there are situations where there is little other choice. Virtual lists are a means to handle lists of *many* items. The example below has 10,000,000 items. When editing rows, the serial # is not editable. Change the "Nag level" to see what is possible with a text overlay

data.name: label5.Text
data.value: This is a simple file system explorer. It is *not* a namespace explorer -- it only handles files and directories. One interesting bit is accessing the Shell icon and type descriptions for files. If you choose an empty folder, you will see an example of an empty list message. Right clicking on the header will let you choose which columns are visible. The 'Attributes' column is an example of a FlagRenderer. You can save the current state of the view and restore it latter.

data.name: label12.Text
data.value: The ListViewPrinter class makes printing a ListView ridiciously easy. The format of the report can be easily customised: the styles Minimal, Modern and Too Much! are just some examples. N.B The preview below is not a full print previewer -- it only shows the first two pages of the report.

data.name: label26.Text
data.value: This is a FastObjectListView, named because it trades functionality for speed. It cannot be put into Tile view, and it can't show groups on XP, but otherwise it acts just like a normal ObjectListView -- only much faster! This panel also show hyperlinks: all occupations are linked to the ObjectListView website, except those starting with "s".

data.name: label42.Text
data.value: The TreeDataListView is a data bound TreeListView. The hierarchy is constructed from information in the data source. Each row needs a unique key (in this case, "Id" column), plus a column that identifies the parent in the hierarchy (in this case, "ParentId" column).

data.name: label30.Text
data.value: These ObjectListViews demonstrate the drag and drop support that ObjectListViews provide. All ObjectListViews can initiate drags and/or receive drops on the list itself, on items, between items or even on subitems. Try dragging some rows into an open Word to see inter-application drag and drop in action. These two lists show dragging between lists and rearranging items within a list (they are NOT sortable since that would negate the value of rearranging the items).
